e design. At the end of February 2009 an Elys\u00e9e [[hatchback]] joined the range, replacing the previous Citro\u00ebn Fukang.\n\nIt is powered by the 1.6 L (1587 cc) [[PSA TU engine|PSA TU5 JP4]] engine, featuring 16 valves [[DOHC]] design and producing {{Convert|109|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on|lk=in}}.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Elysee8.jpg|Promotional image\nFile:Citro\u00ebn Elys\u00e9e China 2012-06-16.JPG|Citro\u00ebn Elys\u00e9e front (2002\u20132008)\nFile:Citro\u00ebn Elys\u00e9e rear China 2012-04-28.JPG|Citro\u00ebn Elys\u00e9e rear (2002\u20132008)\nFile:Citro\u00ebn C-Elys\u00e9e sedan China 2012-04-15.jpg|Citro\u00ebn C-Elys\u00e9e front (2008\u20132010)\nFile:Citro\u00ebn C-Elys\u00e9e sedan facelift China 2015-04-06.jpg|Citro\u00ebn C-Elys\u00e9e front (2011\u20132013)\nFile:Citro\u00ebn Elys\u00e9e VIP 01 China 2017-03-19.jpg|Citro\u00ebn Elys\u00e9e VIP (2005\u20132010)\nFile:Citro\u00ebn C-Elys\u00e9e hatch 01 China 2012-06-16.jpg|Citro\u00ebn Elys\u00e9e hatch (front)\nFile:Citro\u00ebn C-Elys\u00e9e hatch 02 China 2012-06-16.jpg|Citro\u00ebn Elys\u00e9e hatch (rear)\n</gallery>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Second generation (2013\u2013present)==\n{{Main|Citro\u00ebn C Elys\u00e9e}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name         = Citro\u00ebn C-Elys\u00e9e\n| image        = Citro\u00ebn C-Elys\u00e9e II (left) & Citro\u00ebn C-Elys\u00e9e II facelift China 2017-03-25.jpg\n| manufacturer = [[Citro\u00ebn]]\n| production   = 2013\u2013present\n| model_years  = 2014\u2013present\n| assembly     = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[People's Republic of China|China]]<br>[[Vigo]], [[Spain]]\n| engine       = 1.6 L ''EC5 CNG'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] ([[Petrol engine|petrol]])<br>1.6 L ''NFP'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] ([[Petrol engine|petrol]])\n| transmission = 5-speed [[manual transmission|manual]]<br/>6-speed [[automatic transmission|automatic]]<br/>4-speed [[automatic transmission|automatic]]\n| class        = [[Small family car]] ([[C-segment|C]])\n| layout       = [[FF layout]]\n| body_style   = 4-door [[Sedan (car)|saloon]]\n| wheelbase    = {{Convert|2652|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}  \n| length       = {{Convert|4427|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} \n| width        = {{Convert|1748|mm|in||abbr=on}} \n| height       = {{Convert|1476|mm|in||abbr=on}}\n}}\n[[File:Citroen C-Elysee 1.6 HDi Seduction 2013 (11808697755).jpg|thumb|left|Citro\u00ebn C-Elys\u00e9e in Chile]]\n{{main|Peugeot 301 (2012)}}\nThe second generation, called '''Citro\u00ebn C-Elys\u00e9e''', is built in [[Vigo]], [[Spain]], along with the [[Peugeot 301 (2012)|Peugeot 301]], on which it is based, for markets in [[North Africa]], [[South America]] and [[Western Europe]] (Belgium, France and Luxembourg),  [[Eastern Europe]] and [[Southern Europe]]. The C-Elys\u00e9e is also manufactured in [[China]], as its predecessor.\n\n===2017 facelift===\n[[File:Citro\u00ebn C-Elys\u00e9e II facelift China 2017-03-24.jpg|thumb|left|Citro\u00ebn C-Elys\u00e9e facelift (China)]]\nA facelift was presented at the end of 2016 and sales began in the second quarter of 2017, with the main changes being the front lights (with LED DRLs) and rear lights, and a multimedia touchscreen entertainment system compatible with [[Android Auto]], Apple [[Carplay]]. The car also offers a rear camera as an option.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Citro\u00ebn C-Elys\u00e9e WTCC==\n[[File:Citroen (9819942474).jpg|thumb|right|2014 [[Citro\u00ebn C-Elys\u00e9e|Citro\u00ebn C-Elys\u00e9e WTCC]]]] In 2013, '''Citro\u00ebn Racing''' created a new sub-division, the [[Citro\u00ebn World Touring Car Team]], in order to begin to run in addition in the 2014 [[World Touring Car Championship]]. The name '''Citro\u00ebn C-Elys\u00e9e WTCC''' has been chosen for the race car running in this world competition. It was developed in a few months, thanks to the experience of the [[Citro\u00ebn World Rally Team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ptW8ecvwRhA|title=Citro\u00ebn Racing - Projet M43 WTCC : Citro\u00ebn WTCC 2014|date=2014-03-31|accessdate=2014-11-08}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Citro\u00ebn World Touring Car Team]] won fourteen victories out of the fifteen first races of the [[2014 World Touring Car Championship season|2014 WTCC season]], in spite of the handicap of the 60&nbsp;kg Compensation Weight put to the leading cars. The [[Citro\u00ebn World Touring Car Team|Citro\u00ebn/Total WTCC Team]] won the ''Manufacturer's WTCC Championship'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=btoF3iJGGvA|title=One year to win - Citro\u00ebn WTCC 2014|date=2014-10-12|accessdate=2014-11-08}}</ref> 5 races before the end of the season, after the [[2014 FIA WTCC Race of China, Shanghai|2014 Shanghai]] first race, where Citro\u00ebn recorded a magnificent one-two-three-four. The [[Citro\u00ebn World Touring Car Team]] pilots also got the three first ranks of the Drivers' World Touring Car Championship.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Sales==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\";\"\n|- align=\"center\"\n| style=\"background:#e2e2e2;\"|'''Year'''\n| style=\"background:#e2e2e2;\"|'''Worldwide Production'''\n| style=\"background:#e2e2e2;\"|'''Worldwide sales'''\n| style=\"background:#e2e2e2;\"|'''Notes'''\n|-\n|2009\n| align=\"center\" |76,000<ref name=\"Engine specs from PSA Peugeot Citro\u00ebn\">{{cite web|title=Engine specs from PSA Peugeot Citro\u00ebn|url=http://www.info-financiere.fr/upload/BWR/8888/01/FCBWR066301_20110422.pdf|work=Creator and designer|publisher=PSA Peugeot Citro\u00ebn|accessdate=4 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605214832/http://www.info-financiere.fr/upload/BWR/8888/01/FCBWR066301_20110422.pdf|archive-date=5 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |75,500<ref name=\"Engine specs from PSA Peugeot Citro\u00ebn\"/>\n|{{TBA}}\n|-\n|2010\n| align=\"center\" |72,000<ref name=\"Engine specs from PSA Peugeot Citro\u00ebn\"/>\n| align=\"center\" |71,800<ref name=\"Engine specs from PSA Peugeot Citro\u00ebn\"/>\n|{{TBA}}\n|-\n|2011\n| align=\"center\" |66,327<ref name=\"PSA Annual Report 2012\">