{"title_page": "La Sierra Heights", "text_new": "'''La Sierra Heights''', '''La Sierra Hills''', and '''Norco Hills''' are informal names for the northernmost section of the range known as the [[Temescal Mountains]], located in northwestern Riverside County, California. The section begins on the south bank of the [[Santa Ana River]] and extends southward between the valleys occupied by the City of [[Riverside, California|Riverside]] to the east and the Cities of [[Norco, California|Norco]] and [[Corona, California|Corona]] to the west. A [[Gap (landform)|gap]] or [[portezuela]] connects these valleys and separates this range from [[Arlington Mountain]] and the balance of the range to the south.\n\nThese heights vary in height between the informally named [[La Sierra Summit]], just over 1500 feet,<ref>USGS Map Name:  Corona North, CA, 1505 feet, {{coord|33|56|37|N|117|30|40|W|}}</ref> to the hill at [[Grape Benchmark]] at 1084 feet.<ref>USGS Map Name:  Corona North, CA, Grape benchmark, 1084 feet, {{coord|33|53|34|N|117|32|01|W|}}</ref>  Other summits include [[Hole Benchmark]], 1261 feet,<ref>USGS Map Name:  Corona North, CA, Hole benchmark, 1261 feet, {{coord|33|55|51|N|117|30|20|W|}}</ref> [[Linn Benchmark]], 1495 feet<ref>USGS Map Name:  Corona North, CA, Linn benchmark, 1495 feet, {{coord|33|54|38|N|117|30|52|W|}}</ref> and the informally named [[Rattlesnake Peak]], 1421 feet.<ref>[http://www.peakbagger.com/peak.aspx?pid=-19669  Rattlesnake Norco California, United States], from peakbagger.com accessed November 21, 2013; 1421 feet, {{coord|33|55|05|N|117|31|50|W|}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{-}}\n\n[[Category:Temescal Mountains]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Riverside County, California]]\n[[Category:Hills of California]]\n\n\n{{RiversideCountyCA-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''La Sierra Heights''', '''La Sierra Hills''', and '''Norco Hills''' are informal names for the northernmost section of the range known as the [[Temescal Mountains]], located in northwestern Riverside County, California. The section begins on the south bank of the [[Santa Ana River]] and extends southward between the valleys occupied by the City of [[Riverside, California|Riverside]] to the east and the Cities of [[Norco, California|Norco]] and [[Corona]] to the west. A [[Gap (landform)|gap]] or [[portezuela]] connects these valleys and separates this range from [[Arlington Mountain]] and the balance of the range to the south.\n\nThese heights vary in height between the informally named [[La Sierra Summit]], just over 1500 feet,<ref>USGS Map Name:  Corona North, CA, 1505 feet, {{coord|33|56|37|N|117|30|40|W|}}</ref> to the hill at [[Grape Benchmark]] at 1084 feet.<ref>USGS Map Name:  Corona North, CA, Grape benchmark, 1084 feet, {{coord|33|53|34|N|117|32|01|W|}}</ref>  Other summits include [[Hole Benchmark]], 1261 feet,<ref>USGS Map Name:  Corona North, CA, Hole benchmark, 1261 feet, {{coord|33|55|51|N|117|30|20|W|}}</ref> [[Linn Benchmark]], 1495 feet<ref>USGS Map Name:  Corona North, CA, Linn benchmark, 1495 feet, {{coord|33|54|38|N|117|30|52|W|}}</ref> and the informally named [[Rattlesnake Peak]], 1421 feet.<ref>[http://www.peakbagger.com/peak.aspx?pid=-19669  Rattlesnake Norco California, United States], from peakbagger.com accessed November 21, 2013; 1421 feet, {{coord|33|55|05|N|117|31|50|W|}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Temescal Mountains]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Riverside County, California]]\n[[Category:Hills of California]]\n\n\n{{-}}\n{{RiversideCountyCA-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Netoholic", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/La_Sierra_Heights"}
